### CHAPTER LIX.

1\. The sage asked the spirit of wisdom (2) thus: 'What are the vices of
priests? 3. What are the vices of warriors? 4. What are the vices of
husbandmen? 5. And what are the vices of artizans <span
id="fr_573"></span>[4](#fn_565.md)?'

6\. The spirit of wisdom answered (7) thus: 'The vices of priests are
heresy, covetousness, negligence,

<span id="page_106">p. 106</span>

trafficking (sû*d*akîh) <span id="fr_574"></span>[1](#fn_566.md), attention
to trifles, and unbelief in the religion.

8\. 'The vices of warriors are oppression, violence, promise-breaking,
unmercifulness (an-a*v*ôkhshâgâ-vandîh), ostentation (dakhshîh) <span
id="fr_575"></span>[2](#fn_567.md), haughtiness, and arrogance.

9\. 'The vices of husbandmen are ignorance, enviousness, ill-will, and
maliciousness.

10\. '*And* the vices of artizans are unbelief, want of thanksgiving,
improper muttering *of prayers*, moroseness, and abusiveness.'

